(o.b)(\"li\",{parentName:\"ol\"},Object(o.b)(\"p\",{parentName:\"li\"},Object(o.b)(\"strong\",{parentName:\"p\"},\"Thetas\"),\": Geometric function decay rate. For example, if the time unit for the model is weekly, it will represent the percentage of effect each week that is carried over to the next week.\")),Object(o.b)(\"li\",{parentName:\"ol\"},Object(o.b)(\"p\",{parentName:\"li\"},Object(o.b)(\"strong\",{parentName:\"p\"},\"Shapes\"),\": Weibull parameter that controls the decay shape between exponential and s-shape. The larger, the more s-shape, the smaller, the more L-shape.\")),Object(o.b)(\"li\",{parentName:\"ol\"},Object(o.b)(\"p\",{parentName:\"li\"},Object(o.b)(\"strong\",{parentName:\"p\"},\"Scales\"),\": Weibull parameter that controls the position of the decay inflection point. Recommended bounds are between 0 and 0.1. This is  because scale can inflate adstocking half-life siginificantly.\")),Object(o.b)(\"li\",{parentName:\"ol\"},Object(o.b)(\"p\",{parentName:\"li\"},Object(o.b)(\"strong\",{parentName:\"p\"},\"Alphas\"),\": Hill function (Diminishing returns) parameter that controls the shape between exponential and s-shape. The larger the alpha, the more S-shape. The smaller, the more C-shape.\")),Object(o.b)(\"li\",{parentName:\"ol\"},Object(o.b)(\"p\",{parentName:\"li\"},Object(o.b)(\"strong\",{parentName:\"p\"},\"Gammas\"),\": Hill function (Diminishing returns) parameter that controls the inflection point. The larger the gamma, the later the inflection point in the response curve.\")))),Object(o.b)(\"li\",{parentName:\"ol\"},Object(o.b)(\"p\",{parentName:\"li\"},Object(o.b)(\"strong\",{parentName:\"p\"},\"Understanding how adstock affects media transformation:\")),Object(o.b)(\"ol\",{parentName:\"li\"},Object(o.b)(\"li\",{parentName:\"ol\"},\"In order to make more informed decisions to define hyperparameter values, it is very helpful to know which hyperparameter is doing what, during the media variables transformation. The plot function f.plotAdstockCurves helps you understand exactly that.\"),Object(o.b)(\"li\",{parentName:\"ol\"},\"Below we may find an example with different theta values for the geometric adstocking function. You may observe this is a one parameter (theta) function. Assuming the time unit is a week, we can see that when theta is 0.9, it means that 90% of the media effect each week is carried over to the next week. The adstocking halflife is reached after 8 weeks (halflife value in legend). In other words, it takes 8 weeks until the media effect decays to half when theta = 0.9. This should help you to have a more tangible feeling about values for theta and if they make sense for certain channels.\")))),Object(o.b)(\"img\",{alt:\"adstockintro chart\",src:Object(i.a)(\"/img/adstockintro.png\")}),Object(o.b)(\"p\",null,\"Similar to the geometric function above, the Weibull plot visualises the two-parameter (scale & shape) from the Weibull function. The upper plot shows changes in scale while keeping shape constant. We can observe that the larger the scale, the later the inflection point. When scale=0.5 and shape = 2, it takes 18 weeks until the media effect decays to half (see legend). The lower plot shows changes in shape while keeping scale constant. When the shape is smaller, the curve rather takes an L-shape. When the shape is larger, the curve rather turns into an inverted S-shape.\"),Object(o.b)(\"img\",{alt:\"adstockintro2 chart\",src:Object(i.a)(\"/img/adstockintro2.png\")}),Object(o.b)(\"p\",null,\"The following media transformation bounds to set up are hill function\\u2019s (diminishing returns) curves scale and shape parameters. The theory of diminishing returns holds that each additional unit of advertising increases the response, but at a declining rate. This key marketing principle is reflected in marketing mix models as a variable transformation. You may observe below the differences in diminishing returns curves when changing alpha and gamma parameter ranges of values per channel. The higher the values for alpha, the more S-shape, the lower, the more C-shape.  Recommended ranges are  between 0.5 and 3 in order to provide reasonable curves that make sense for marketing variables. Whereas, the higher the values for gamma, the later the inflection point will appear. Late inflection points mean that the channel in question will have more room for investment and will reach a saturation point at higher investment levels.\"),Object(o.b)(\"img\",{alt:\"hillFunction1 chart\",src:Object(i.a)(\"/img/hillFunction1.png\")}),Object(o.b)(\"h2\",{id:\"accessing-plotted-results\"},\"Accessing plotted results\"),Object(o.b)(\"p\",null,\"Once all trials and iterations are finished, the model will proceed to plot different charts that will help you assess best models based on NRMSE and a media variables decomposition quality score for contribution of marketing channels. You may find all model plots like below example within the plot_folder you have set on the \\u2018run models\\u2019 step. You will see that there is a model unique ID associated with each model and chart saved in the folder. In the example below mod_ID = 1_22_3.\"),Object(o.b)(\"img\",{alt:\"ModelResults1 chart\",src:Object(i.a)(\"/img/ModelResults1.png\")}),Object(o.b)(\"h2\",{id:\"using-the-budget-allocator\"},\"Using the budget allocator\"),Object(o.b)(\"p\",null,\"The budget allocator is also named optimizer. It provides the optimal media mix, which maximizes the return out of a certain spend level, while holding true to a set of constraints. Please note that the budget allocator will only output reasonable optimization when the MMM result makes sense, meaning all media channels have already found reasonable hyperparameters for adstocking and S-curving and the responses for each channel is meeting your expectations. Otherwise, the budget allocator output is not interpretable. Technically, the budget allocator consumes the response curve (Hill function) for each channel provided by the MMM result and conducts the solver for nonlinear optimization. The gradient-based algorithms (augmented Lagrangian / AUGLAG for global optimization and Method of Moving Asymptotes / MMA for local optimization) are chosen to solve the\\nnonlinear optimization problem with equal and unequal constraints. For details see \",Object(o.b)(\"a\",{parentName:\"p\",href:\"https://nlopt.readthedocs.io/en/latest/NLopt_Algorithms/\"},\"here\"),\".\"),Object(o.b)(\"p\",null,\"The first thing you will have to \",Object(o.b)(\"strong\",{parentName:\"p\"},\"define\"),\" is the \",Object(o.b)(\"strong\",{parentName:\"p\"},\"model unique ID\"),\" from the results in the previous section that you would like to use for the optimizer. Continuing with the example above, setting \",Object(o.b)(\"strong\",{parentName:\"p\"},'modID = \"1_22_3\"'),\" could be an example of a selected model from the list of best models in \",Object(o.b)(\"strong\",{parentName:\"p\"},\"'model_output_collect$allSolutions'\"),\" results object.\"),Object(o.b)(\"pre\",null,Object(o.b)(\"code\",{parentName:\"pre\"},'optim_result <- f.budgetAllocator(modID = \"1_22_3\"\\n                                ...\\n                                ...\\n)\\n')),Object(o.b)(\"p\",null,\"Our current budget allocator has two scenarios:\"),Object(o.b)(\"ul\",null,Object(o.b)(\"li\",{parentName:\"ul\"},Object(o.b)(\"strong\",{parentName:\"li\"},\"Maximum historical response\"),\" (max_historical_response): Assuming two years of data for five media channels is used to build the model. Total spend was 1MM \\u20ac with 40/30/15/10/5 split for both channels and total return was 2MM\\u20ac. The budget allocator will output the optimum split for the historical spend level of 1MM\\u20ac. For example, a maximum return of 2.5MM would be achieved with 35/25/20/12/8 split of the 1MM\\u20ac spent.\")),Object(o.b)(\"pre\",null,Object(o.b)(\"code\",{parentName:\"pre\"},'optim_result <- f.budgetAllocator(\\n                            modID = \